  <div class="article-content">
    <section id="introduction" class="reveal">
<p>Sometime in late 2024, a team of researchers at Merck stared at data that most of the pharmaceutical industry had written off as a pipe dream. A pill—a simple, once-daily oral tablet—had just obliterated LDL cholesterol levels by nearly 60% in a large clinical trial. For context, that is the kind of reduction previously achievable only through biweekly or monthly injections of monoclonal antibodies costing thousands of dollars a year, administered via subcutaneous needle, and prescribed by a vanishingly small fraction of physicians. The oral drug, enlicitide decanoate, had done what decades of drug development had failed to do: shrink a massive protein-blocking mechanism into something you could swallow with a glass of water on an empty stomach before breakfast.</p>
<p>The results, published in February 2026 in the <em>New England Journal of Medicine</em>, were unambiguous. In 2,909 patients with or at risk for atherosclerotic cardiovascular disease, enlicitide reduced LDL cholesterol by 57.1% at 24 weeks compared with a 3.0% increase in the placebo group—an adjusted between-group difference of 55.8 percentage points (95% CI, −60.9 to −50.7; P<0.001). The effect held at 52 weeks. The safety profile was statistically indistinguishable from placebo. And the FDA, in a move that signals just how seriously regulators are taking this, awarded enlicitide a National Priority Voucher to accelerate its review.</p>
<p>This is, by any reasonable measure, a genuine technological achievement. But the celebration comes with an asterisk the size of a coronary artery. Because the question that has haunted cholesterol science for decades remains stubbornly unanswered for this particular drug: does lowering LDL cholesterol this aggressively actually prevent heart attacks and save lives? The answer, as of today, is that we don't know. And that uncertainty reveals something important about the way we wage war on cardiovascular disease.</p>
</section>

<section id="the-impossible-pill" class="reveal">
<h2>The Impossible Pill</h2>
<p>To appreciate what enlicitide represents, you need to understand why nobody thought it could exist. PCSK9 inhibitors—the class of drugs that block a protein called proprotein convertase subtilisin/kexin type 9—have been around since 2015, when the FDA approved evolocumab (Repatha) and alirocumab (Praluent). These are monoclonal antibodies: large, complex proteins engineered to bind to PCSK9 in the bloodstream and prevent it from degrading LDL receptors on liver cells. More LDL receptors means more cholesterol clearance. Simple biology, spectacular results. Evolocumab lowers LDL cholesterol by approximately 60%.</p>
<p>The problem was delivery. Monoclonal antibodies are enormous molecules. They cannot survive the acid bath of the stomach or navigate the intestinal wall intact. They must be injected. And injections, it turns out, are a remarkably effective barrier to widespread adoption. Despite proven efficacy and eventual price reductions, Dr. Ann Marie Navar of UT Southwestern Medical Center—a lead investigator on the enlicitide trials—has documented that most primary care physicians and a substantial minority of cardiologists still do not routinely prescribe injectable PCSK9 therapies. The reasons are partly historical (early cost and insurance barriers), but the injection requirement appears to be a persistent obstacle even after those issues improved.</p>
<p>Enlicitide solves this problem through a feat of molecular engineering. It is not a monoclonal antibody. It is a macrocyclic peptide—a small molecule designed to mimic the binding action of those massive antibodies while being compact enough to survive oral administration. As Merck's Dean Y. Li described it, enlicitide was "designed to deliver PCSK9 antibody-like efficacy and specificity in an easy-to-use pill." The drug binds to PCSK9 in the bloodstream, preventing the protein from interacting with LDL receptors, leaving more receptors available on liver cell surfaces to clear LDL cholesterol from the blood. Same mechanism. Same results. Different delivery.</p>
<p>This is the first oral macrocyclic peptide PCSK9 inhibitor to advance through Phase 3 development. That distinction matters. The pharmaceutical industry has been trying to crack oral PCSK9 inhibition for years. Enlicitide is the first to demonstrate that it can actually work at scale.</p>
</section>

<section id="the-data" class="reveal">
<h2>What the Data Actually Show</h2>
<p>The evidence base for enlicitide now spans three pivotal Phase 3 trials in the CORALreef clinical program, which collectively evaluates over 19,000 participants with hypercholesterolemia. The two published studies tell a consistent story.</p>

<div class="info-card my-12 reveal">
<h4 class="font-serif text-lg font-semibold mb-3 text-primary-700 dark:text-primary-400">CORALreef Lipids Trial — Key Results</h4>
<ul class="space-y-2 text-sm">
<li><strong>Publication:</strong> <em>New England Journal of Medicine</em>, February 2026 (Navar AM, Mikhailova E, Catapano AL, et al.)</li>
<li><strong>Sample Size:</strong> 2,909 adults randomized 2:1 (enlicitide 20 mg vs. placebo) across 168 sites in 14 countries</li>
<li><strong>Population:</strong> Mean age 63 years; 39% women; 97% on statins; mean baseline LDL-C 96.1 mg/dL</li>
<li><strong>LDL-C Reduction at 24 Weeks:</strong> −57.1% with enlicitide vs. +3.0% with placebo (between-group difference: −55.8 pp; P<0.001)</li>
<li><strong>LDL-C Reduction at 52 Weeks:</strong> Between-group difference maintained at −47.6 pp (P<0.001)</li>
<li><strong>Non-HDL-C Reduction:</strong> −53.4 pp vs. placebo at week 24</li>
<li><strong>Apolipoprotein B Reduction:</strong> −50.3 pp vs. placebo at week 24</li>
<li><strong>Lipoprotein(a) Reduction:</strong> −28.2 pp vs. placebo at week 24</li>
<li><strong>Goal Attainment:</strong> 70.3% of enlicitide patients achieved LDL-C <70 mg/dL with ≥50% reduction (vs. 1.5% placebo)</li>
<li><strong>Safety:</strong> Adverse events 64% vs. 62%; serious AEs 10% vs. 12%; discontinuation 3% vs. 4%</li>
</ul>
</div>

<p>The second published trial, CORALreef HeFH, appeared simultaneously in <em>JAMA</em> in January 2026. Led by Dr. Christie M. Ballantyne of Baylor College of Medicine, it enrolled 303 adults with heterozygous familial hypercholesterolemia—a genetic disorder affecting roughly 1 in 250 people that causes dangerously elevated LDL cholesterol from birth. These patients were already on aggressive statin therapy (81.5% on high-intensity statins), and 64.4% were also taking ezetimibe. Even on top of that pharmacological foundation, enlicitide reduced LDL cholesterol by 58.2% versus a 2.6% increase with placebo at 24 weeks (between-group difference: −59.4%; 95% CI, −65.6% to −53.2%; P<0.001). At 52 weeks, the between-group difference actually widened to −61.5%.</p>
<p>The drug also moved the needle on apolipoprotein B (−48.2% vs. +1.8%), non-HDL cholesterol (−52.3% vs. +2.1%), and lipoprotein(a) (−24.7% vs. −1.6%). All P-values less than 0.001. The safety profile was, again, comparable to placebo. A 96.7% trial completion rate suggests tolerability was not a significant issue.</p>
<p>As Dr. Navar put it: "These reductions in LDL cholesterol are the most we have ever achieved with an oral drug by far since the development of statins." That is not hyperbole. It is a factual description of where this drug sits in the pharmacological hierarchy.</p>

<aside class="pull-quote reveal"><p>"These reductions in LDL cholesterol are the most we have ever achieved with an oral drug by far since the development of statins."</p></aside>
</section>

<section id="injection-gap" class="reveal">
<h2>The Injection Gap: Why Delivery Matters More Than You Think</h2>
<p>Here is the uncomfortable reality of cardiovascular medicine in 2026: we already have drugs that can lower LDL cholesterol by 60%. We have had them for a decade. And almost nobody uses them.</p>
<p>Approximately 86 million adults in the United States have hypercholesterolemia. Fewer than half of patients with established atherosclerotic cardiovascular disease currently reach their LDL cholesterol goals, even with available therapies. Nearly 70% of people with ASCVD who are treated with lipid-lowering therapies do not reach target LDL cholesterol levels. These are not obscure statistics. They represent a massive, ongoing failure of implementation.</p>
<p>Injectable PCSK9 inhibitors were supposed to close this gap. They didn't. Despite evolocumab and alirocumab demonstrating consistent LDL reductions of approximately 60%, their real-world uptake has been dismal. Early barriers included annual costs exceeding $14,000 and aggressive insurance prior-authorization requirements. Those barriers have largely fallen—prices have dropped, and some insurers no longer require preauthorization. Yet prescribing rates remain stubbornly low.</p>
<p>Dr. Navar's research group has documented this phenomenon extensively. The injection requirement appears to be the remaining bottleneck. As she told TCTMD at the AHA 2025 presentation: "There are a number of patients who would prefer an oral to an injectable therapy, and I do have patients who will not initiate an injection and only want to take an oral medication." This is not a trivial preference. It is a behavioral reality that has left millions of high-risk patients undertreated.</p>
<p>Enlicitide's value proposition, then, is not primarily about efficacy. The efficacy was already available. It is about access—about converting a proven biological mechanism from a format that physicians and patients resist into one they will actually use. UT Southwestern's analysis noted that LDL-lowering effects with enlicitide were "nearly identical to those seen with injectable antibodies alirocumab and evolocumab and numerically larger than those reported for the siRNA therapy inclisiran."</p>
<p>If enlicitide reaches the market, the question becomes whether an oral formulation can succeed where injections failed. The FDA seems to think the potential is significant enough to warrant expedited review, having granted the drug a National Priority Voucher under the Commissioner's pilot program—a designation reserved for products addressing large unmet medical needs or improving accessibility.</p>
</section>

<section id="mortality-question" class="reveal">
<h2>The Mortality Question Nobody Wants to Talk About</h2>
<p>Now for the part that makes cardiologists shift uncomfortably in their chairs.</p>
<p>Enlicitide lowers LDL cholesterol by 60%. Wonderful. But does lowering LDL cholesterol by 60% prevent heart attacks? Does it save lives? For enlicitide specifically, we have no idea. The CORALreef trials were designed to measure lipid changes, not cardiovascular events. The outcomes trial—CORALreef Outcomes, with over 14,500 enrolled participants—will not report results until approximately December 2029. That is nearly four years from now.</p>
<p>This matters because the relationship between cholesterol reduction and cardiovascular outcomes is more complicated than the pharmaceutical industry's marketing departments would prefer.</p>
<p>The best evidence we have comes from the FOURIER trial, published in the <em>New England Journal of Medicine</em> in 2017. That landmark study randomized 27,564 patients with atherosclerotic cardiovascular disease to injectable evolocumab or placebo on top of statin therapy. Evolocumab lowered LDL cholesterol by 59%—essentially the same reduction enlicitide achieves. Over a median follow-up of 2.2 years, evolocumab reduced the primary composite endpoint (cardiovascular death, MI, stroke, hospitalization for unstable angina, or coronary revascularization) by 15%, and the key secondary endpoint (cardiovascular death, MI, or stroke) by 20%.</p>
<p>Those numbers sound impressive until you look at the absolute risk reductions. The primary endpoint occurred in 9.8% of the evolocumab group versus 11.3% of the placebo group—an absolute difference of 1.5 percentage points. For the secondary endpoint: 5.9% versus 7.4%. As Johns Hopkins cardiologist Michael Blaha noted at the time, the results were somewhat "underwhelming" relative to initial predictions that evolocumab might reduce cardiovascular events by at least 30%.</p>

<aside class="pull-quote reveal"><p>"If this were a cheaper medication, with the wonderful side-effect profile seen here, I think clinicians would be ecstatic about these results."</p></aside>

<p>More troubling is the mortality data. A systematic review and meta-analysis published in <em>Cureus</em> in 2023, examining multiple randomized controlled trials, found that overall, "no significant differences were observed in CV and all-cause mortality between PCSK9 inhibitors and controls." Alirocumab showed a signal for reduced all-cause mortality, but evolocumab did not. A separate meta-analysis in the <em>British Journal of Clinical Pharmacology</em> (2019) confirmed this pattern: PCSK9 inhibitors reduced major adverse cardiovascular events (MH-OR 0.83; 95% CI, 0.78–0.88) but did not significantly reduce all-cause mortality (MH-OR 0.94; 95% CI, 0.84–1.04) or cardiovascular mortality (MH-OR 0.97; 95% CI, 0.86–1.09). The number needed to treat for two years to prevent one MACE event was 89.</p>
<p>A more critical analysis published in <em>Expert Review of Clinical Pharmacology</em> (2020), based on ClinicalTrials.gov data rather than published articles, went further, noting that "PCSK9 inhibitors have not been shown to decrease the risk of mortality in our or any previous review." The authors raised concerns about evolocumab specifically, suggesting the extended follow-up data showed a potentially increased mortality signal—though this remains controversial and contested by the broader cardiology community.</p>
<p>To be clear: the FOURIER trial did demonstrate meaningful reductions in non-fatal cardiovascular events. A prespecified secondary analysis found that in patients with recent myocardial infarction (within 12 months), evolocumab reduced the primary endpoint by 19% with a number needed to treat of just 27 over three years. The benefit was real. But it was concentrated in non-fatal events, and the mortality needle barely moved.</p>
</section>

<section id="cholesterol-hypothesis" class="reveal">
<h2>The Cholesterol Hypothesis, Revisited</h2>
<p>This brings us to the deeper question that enlicitide's arrival forces us to confront: how much of cardiovascular disease is actually about cholesterol?</p>
<p>The standard model—the one that has driven drug development for four decades—goes like this: LDL cholesterol deposits in arterial walls, triggering atherosclerosis, which leads to heart attacks and strokes. Lower the LDL, slow the process, prevent the events. This model is supported by an enormous body of evidence, including genetic studies showing that people born with PCSK9 loss-of-function mutations (who naturally have lower LDL cholesterol) have substantially reduced rates of myocardial infarction. The discovery of the LDL receptor by Michael Brown and Joseph Goldstein at UT Southwestern—work that earned them the Nobel Prize in 1985—remains one of the most consequential findings in modern medicine.</p>
<p>But the model has always been incomplete. Atherosclerosis is fundamentally an inflammatory disease. Cholesterol is a participant, not the sole driver. The CANTOS trial (2017) demonstrated that targeting inflammation directly with canakinumab—without any effect on cholesterol—reduced cardiovascular events. Residual cardiovascular risk persists even in patients who achieve very low LDL levels. And the mortality data from PCSK9 inhibitor trials suggest that there may be diminishing returns to ever-more-aggressive cholesterol lowering, at least over the timeframes studied.</p>
<p>None of this means the cholesterol hypothesis is wrong. It means it is insufficient. And enlicitide arrives at a moment when the field is grappling with this insufficiency. We can now lower LDL cholesterol to levels that would have seemed science-fictional a generation ago—the FOURIER trial got patients down to a median of 30 mg/dL, a level some researchers have called "fetal" because it approximates what humans have at birth. Yet the cardiovascular benefit, while real, has not scaled proportionally with the cholesterol reduction.</p>
<p>The Cholesterol Treatment Trialists' (CTT) Collaboration has established that for every 1 mmol/L (approximately 39 mg/dL) reduction in LDL cholesterol, the risk of major vascular events falls by about 22% over five years. If that relationship held linearly, a 60% LDL reduction should produce enormous cardiovascular benefits. The FOURIER data suggest the relationship may flatten at very low LDL levels—or that the follow-up period was simply too short to capture the full benefit. Both explanations are plausible. Neither is proven.</p>
</section>

<section id="real-world-challenges" class="reveal">
<h2>The Real-World Challenges Ahead</h2>
<p>Even setting aside the outcomes question, enlicitide faces practical hurdles that could limit its real-world impact.</p>
<p>First, the empty-stomach requirement. Enlicitide must be taken on an empty stomach for optimal absorption—a constraint that sounds minor but has historically undermined adherence to other medications. Patients who take morning medications with breakfast, or who have irregular eating schedules, may find this requirement difficult to maintain consistently over years of treatment.</p>
<p>Second, the 52-week follow-up ceiling. The longest published data we have for enlicitide covers one year. Cholesterol-lowering drugs are taken for decades. We do not yet know whether the efficacy is maintained, whether new safety signals emerge, or whether the drug's absorption characteristics change with prolonged use. The CORALreef Extension trial is designed to address this, but results are pending.</p>
<p>Third, the funding question. Every published enlicitide trial was funded by Merck (operating as MSD outside the United States). Dr. Navar received consulting fees from Merck for her work on the study, and she has disclosed consulting relationships with multiple pharmaceutical companies that make lipid-lowering drugs. This does not invalidate the results—industry-funded trials are the norm in drug development, and the data were published in the <em>New England Journal of Medicine</em> and <em>JAMA</em>, journals with rigorous peer review. But it does mean the results have been generated, analyzed, and presented by parties with a financial interest in the drug's success. Independent replication and real-world effectiveness studies will be essential.</p>

<div class="info-card my-12 reveal">
<h4 class="font-serif text-lg font-semibold mb-3 text-primary-700 dark:text-primary-400">What We Know vs. What We Don't</h4>
<ul class="space-y-2 text-sm">
<li><strong>Known:</strong> Enlicitide reduces LDL-C by ~57–60% at 24 weeks, sustained through 52 weeks</li>
<li><strong>Known:</strong> Safety profile comparable to placebo over 52 weeks in ~3,200 patients</li>
<li><strong>Known:</strong> Also reduces ApoB (~50%), non-HDL-C (~53%), and Lp(a) (~28%)</li>
<li><strong>Unknown:</strong> Whether these lipid reductions translate to fewer heart attacks, strokes, or deaths</li>
<li><strong>Unknown:</strong> Long-term safety beyond 52 weeks</li>
<li><strong>Unknown:</strong> Real-world adherence with empty-stomach dosing requirement</li>
<li><strong>Unknown:</strong> Cost and insurance coverage at launch</li>
<li><strong>Timeline:</strong> CORALreef Outcomes trial (14,500+ patients) expected to report ~December 2029</li>
</ul>
</div>

<p>Fourth—and this is the elephant in the examination room—cost. When injectable PCSK9 inhibitors launched at over $14,000 per year, insurers revolted. The resulting prior-authorization battles created a bureaucratic nightmare that suppressed prescribing for years. If Merck prices enlicitide at a premium, the same dynamic could repeat. If they price it competitively, the oral formulation could genuinely transform population-level cholesterol management. The pricing decision may matter more than the clinical data.</p>
</section>

<section id="broader-implications" class="reveal">
<h2>What This Tells Us About Modern Medicine</h2>
<p>Enlicitide is a case study in the paradoxes of pharmaceutical progress. We have achieved something remarkable: the ability to manipulate a single biomarker with extraordinary precision, using a pill that is safe, effective, and convenient. The science is elegant. The engineering is impressive. The clinical data are clean.</p>
<p>And yet.</p>
<p>We are still, fundamentally, optimizing for a surrogate endpoint. LDL cholesterol is not cardiovascular disease. It is a risk factor for cardiovascular disease—an important one, arguably the most important modifiable one, but a risk factor nonetheless. The gap between moving a number on a blood test and preventing a human being from having a heart attack is not trivial. It is the gap that has bedeviled cardiology for decades.</p>
<p>The FOURIER trial showed that injectable PCSK9 inhibition produced a 15% relative reduction in the primary composite cardiovascular endpoint and a 20% reduction in the key secondary endpoint over 2.2 years of follow-up. Those are meaningful numbers. But they are not the transformative results that a 60% LDL reduction might have predicted. And the absence of a clear mortality benefit—across multiple meta-analyses examining tens of thousands of patients—suggests that we may be approaching the limits of what cholesterol reduction alone can accomplish.</p>
<p>Dr. William Boden, writing in an accompanying <em>NEJM</em> editorial, called the enlicitide results "impressive" and described them as "compelling evidence" that the oral pill matches injectable PCSK9 inhibitors. He emphasized that a simpler oral formulation could facilitate greater medication adherence and more effective long-term LDL-C lowering. He is right about all of that. The question is whether better adherence to cholesterol lowering is the rate-limiting step in preventing cardiovascular death, or whether we need to be targeting something else entirely—or in addition.</p>

<aside class="pull-quote reveal"><p>"Fewer than half of patients with established atherosclerotic cardiovascular disease currently reach LDL cholesterol goals."</p></aside>

<p>Consider the broader landscape. Heart disease remains the leading cause of death globally. Approximately 85% of cardiovascular deaths are attributable to heart disease. We have statins, ezetimibe, bempedoic acid, injectable PCSK9 inhibitors, inclisiran (an siRNA therapy), and now potentially an oral PCSK9 inhibitor. We have more pharmacological tools for lowering cholesterol than for almost any other single biomarker in medicine. And cardiovascular disease continues to kill more people than any other condition on earth.</p>
<p>This is not an argument against enlicitide. It is an argument for epistemic humility about what any single drug—no matter how impressive its mechanism or how clean its trial data—can accomplish against a disease as complex and multifactorial as atherosclerosis.</p>
</section>

<section id="the-road-to-2029" class="reveal">
<h2>The Road to 2029</h2>
<p>The definitive answer to whether enlicitide prevents cardiovascular events will come from the CORALreef Outcomes trial, which has completed enrollment with over 14,500 participants and is projected to report results in December 2029. That trial is designed to measure what the lipid trials could not: actual heart attacks, strokes, and deaths.</p>
<p>In the meantime, the FDA review process is underway. If approved—and the National Priority Voucher suggests regulators are inclined to move quickly—enlicitide could reach the market based on its lipid-lowering data alone, with the outcomes trial serving as a post-marketing confirmation. This is standard practice for cholesterol drugs; statins were initially approved on the basis of LDL reduction before the landmark outcomes trials (4S, WOSCOPS, CARE) demonstrated mortality benefits years later.</p>
<p>The precedent is encouraging but not guaranteed. Statins ultimately proved their worth in outcomes trials. Ezetimibe took over a decade to demonstrate a modest cardiovascular benefit in IMPROVE-IT. And some cholesterol-lowering drugs—torcetrapib, which raised HDL cholesterol but increased mortality—have failed spectacularly when outcomes data arrived. The history of cardiovascular pharmacology is littered with drugs that moved the right numbers in the wrong direction.</p>
<p>Enlicitide has a significant advantage over those cautionary tales: it works through the same mechanism as drugs (evolocumab and alirocumab) that have already demonstrated cardiovascular event reduction. The biological plausibility is strong. The question is not whether PCSK9 inhibition reduces cardiovascular events—FOURIER and ODYSSEY OUTCOMES have established that it does—but whether the oral formulation delivers the same downstream benefits, and whether those benefits are large enough to justify the cost and complexity of adding another drug to patients' regimens.</p>
</section>

<section id="conclusion" class="reveal">
<h2>The Power and the Limits of a Number</h2>
<p>In 1985, Brown and Goldstein won the Nobel Prize for discovering the LDL receptor. That discovery launched a four-decade campaign to lower cholesterol, a campaign that has saved millions of lives through statins and reshaped how we think about cardiovascular prevention. Enlicitide is, in many ways, the culmination of that campaign—the most powerful oral cholesterol-lowering tool ever created, built on a foundation of Nobel Prize-winning science, delivered in the most patient-friendly format imaginable.</p>
<p>It is also, potentially, a monument to a particular way of thinking about disease: identify a biomarker, develop a drug to move it, declare victory. That approach has worked brilliantly for many conditions. For cardiovascular disease, it has worked well but not completely. The gap between moving LDL cholesterol and preventing death is narrower than skeptics claim but wider than enthusiasts admit.</p>
<p>We have gotten remarkably good at manipulating cholesterol numbers. Enlicitide may be the best we have ever been. The 14,500 patients in the CORALreef Outcomes trial will tell us whether being the best at moving a number is the same as being the best at saving a life. Until then, we are left with a genuinely impressive pill, a genuinely important question, and the genuinely uncomfortable possibility that the answer might be more complicated than either side wants it to be.</p>
<p>That is not a reason to dismiss enlicitide. It is a reason to take it seriously—and to demand that we hold it to the same evidentiary standard we would apply to any drug that aspires to change how we prevent the leading cause of death in the developed world. The pill works. The question is what "works" means.</p>
</section>

